            "headline": "Applied Learning Scientist",
            "summary": "I am a learning scientist on a mission to craft the next generation of learning experiences. \n\nOver the past 17 years, I have worked on the design, evaluation, and improvement of a number of adaptive learning systems for learners, from 3-year-olds to professionals, for learning math, science, reading, medical science, and more.\n\nI have also worked on assessments of 21st century competencies, curriculum design for project-based learning with VR, and learning design for a college experiential learning program. \n\nI think great learning experiences come about when we put the learners first, engineer for evidence, and learn as we go. And we do it together in interdisciplinary teams. \n\nMy work is often a blend of cognitive psychology, learning analytics, efficacy research, psychometrics, and partnerships (I can't do it all myself!). You can find me translating research to learning product design and strategy, leading efficacy studies, pulling insights from learning analytics to inform product design and improvements, creating and validating assessments, establishing and maintaining partnerships with various organizations and consultants. I enjoy every aspect!\n\nI also enjoy sharing what I've learned. Some of my recent publications:\n- The Handbook of Research on Innovative Approaches to Early Childhood Development and School Readiness: https://www.igi-global.com/book/handbook-research-innovative-approaches-early/272193. \n- A couple chapters on human-centered design and data analytics in the Learning Engineering Toolkit: https://www.routledge.com/Learning-Engineering-Toolkit-Evidence-Based-Practices-from-the-Learning/Goodell-Kolodner/p/book/9781032232829\n- A chapter on applying learning engineering to create math games for 2-3 year olds: https://link.springer.com/referenceworkentry/10.1007/978-3-319-17727-4_192-1",
